Many researchers reported on the improved quantum yield of NCDs (14.0–19.4%) [21,24] in comparison to CDs (7.2–10.4%) [18,21] as observed in this work. NCDs solution was first diluted to obtain similar photoluminescence before photoluminescence measurement. The photoluminescent images of CD, CD-MFC, NCD and NCD-MFC dispersed in water (Fig. 2
                        ) exhibited significant variation brightness. CD-MFC and NCD-MFC samples are brighter than CD and NCD samples, respectively under UV illuminations. The variation was further analyzed using ImageJ that generates RGB result (Fig. S3-S6). The distribution of grey pixel intensity of CD and NCD samples is broad without the presence of MFC, ranging from 86 to 235 and 63 to 238, respectively (Fig. 3
                        ). After dispersion in a low concentration of MFC network, the grey pixel intensity distribution of CD-MFC and NCD-MFC samples skewed to right within the higher range of 152–234 and 117–214, respectively. The changes resulted in higher brightness to the naked eye when comparing CD to CD-MFC or NCD to NCD-MFC samples as mentioned earlier. Under UV irradiation, all the samples containing MFC showed a great increment of green pixel intensity in comparison to the samples without MFC. The presence of MFC improved the photoluminescence of the CD and NCD samples due to the reduction of agglomeration observed using HRTEM. Photoluminescence spectroscopy results (Fig. S7) further confirmed that the increment of MFC content in NCD-MFC sample promoted the growth of photoluminescence of NCDs even only 0.05 wt% of MFC was present in NCD-MFC sample.

The photoluminescent lifetime of CDs within the range of 5.3–13.2 ns was reported by others [29,30], depending on temperature or irradiation condition. Even NCDs were coated on Ce3+: YAG phosphor-in-glass substrate, the similar photoluminescent lifetime to NCDs solution was reported, namely 6.51 ns [31]. Although CDs have been embedded into PVA by several research teams [32,27], the detailed characteristics and application of these thin film as a photoluminescent sensor are yet to be widely reported. For instance, it is important to understand the effects of MFC on the transparency of photoluminescent thin film. This is because the penetration of UV to excite CDs in thin film can be affected by MFC, resulting changes in quenching. The transparency of the films was first determined by percentage of light transmittance which is a measure of their capability to transmit light at different wavelengths. At long visible wavelengths (≥ 530 nm), all the photoluminescent thin films (PVA/CD, PVA/CD-MFC, PVA/NCD and PVA/NCD-MFC thin films) synthesized in this work exhibited high percentage of transmittance (≥ 78%) of light as shown in Fig. 5
                        . As the wavelength become shorter, PVA/CD and PVA/CD-MFC thin films experienced a sudden decrease of light transmittance, while PVA/NCD and PVA/NCD-MFC thin films only underwent a gradual decrement. It was also noted that both PVA/NCD and PVA/NCD-MFC thin films had a higher percentage of transmittance within the UV range (200–400 nm) compared to PVA/CD and PVA/CD-MFC. The similar findings were reported by others [27,33] who incorporated NCD into PVA [27] and polymethyl methacrylate [33]. They also reported an increment of light absorbance or decrement of light transmittance within the UV range. Based on their observations, NCDs could work better in the films when it was excited at 350 nm. The presence of MFC which aids dispersion of NCDs further improved the light transmittance of the films, making it a better candidate of sensor. Nevertheless, all four thin films in this work exhibited photoluminescent properties as green light was observed under UV irradiation (Fig. 6
                        ).

The photoluminescence of PVA/CD, PVA/CD-MFC, PVA/NCD and PVA/NCD-MFC thin films were measured before and after tartrazine quenching to study the changes of their photoluminescence. Comparing to PVA/CD thin film, PVA/CD-MFC thin film suffered from a reduction in fluorescent intensity even before tartrazine quenching (Fig. 8
                         (a) and (b)). The reduction of photoluminescence could be related to the reduction of light transmittance of PVA/CD-MFC thin film compared to PVA/CD thin film (Fig. 5). PVA/CD thin film experienced about 50% reduction in fluorescent intensity after tartrazine quenching. However, such changes were not observed for PVA/CD-MFC thin film. The sensing potential of PVA/CD-MFC thin film was greatly affected by the presence of MFC. With the presence of MFC, PVA/NCD-MFC thin film showed a better fluorescent intensity than PVA/NCD thin film as shown in Fig. 8 (c) and (d). Moreover, the quenching effects were amplified by MFC in PVA/NCD-MFC thin film. Such observation has not been reported by others [16,37] and it could be related to the reduction of agglomeration of NCDs in the three-dimensional network of MFC without significant reduction of light transmittance. NCDs with –NH2 groups could interact with MFC better and CDs. The RGB results generated from ImageJ analysis also supported the photoluminescence spectroscopy result of PVA/NCD-MFC, showing the reduction of total grey pixel intensity (Fig. 9
                        ). The reduction mainly caused by the reduction of green and blue pixel intensity after quenching (Fig. S9). Similarly, Ahmad et al. [32] also shown the successfulness of using CIE RGB to measure the digital image of the CDs in PVA matrix deposited on a glass slide. Thus, PVA/NCD-MFC thin film was identified to be highly potential in the development of tartrazine sensor. It can be used to analyze tartrazine content quantitatively via photoluminescence spectroscopy or qualitatively through smart phone and image processer. Most importantly, it serves as chemical data storage film as it can be dried and analyzed without the need to transfer liquid samples.
